  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "In the United States, money laundering is a serious federal crime with severe penalties. The specific penalties can vary depending on the circumstances of the case, the amount of money involved, and other factors. Below is a general overview of the penalties for money laundering under federal law:\n\n1. **Criminal Penalties**:\n   - **Imprisonment**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years** in federal prison for each count. In cases involving terrorism financing, the maximum penalty can be increased to **25 years**.\n   - **Fines**: Fines can be substantial. For individuals, fines can reach **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater. For organizations, fines can be **up to $1 million or twice the value of the laundered funds**.\n   - **Enhanced Penalties for Certain Cases**: If the money laundering involves proceeds from drug trafficking or other serious crimes, the penalties may be even harsher.\n\n2. **Civil Penalties**:\n   - **Forfeiture**: The government can seize property, funds, or assets involved in the money laundering scheme or derived from illegal activities.\n   - **Fines**: Civil penalties can include fines up to **$10,000** or the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.\n\n3. **Additional Consequences**:\n   - **Reputation Damage**: A money laundering conviction can severely harm an individual\u2019s or business\u2019s reputation.\n   - **Loss of Professional Licenses**: Certain professions (e.g., banking, law, accounting) may revoke licenses or bar individuals convicted of money laundering from practicing.\n   - **Immigration Consequences**: Non-citizens convicted of money laundering may face deportation or inadmissibility to the U.S.\n\nThe penalties are outlined in various federal statutes, including the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957) and the **Bank Secrecy Act** (31 U.S.C. \u00a7 5311 et seq.). Each case is unique, and the actual penalties imposed depend on the specifics of the case and the discretion of the court.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
